	<li class="comment even depth-2" id="comment-6165" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Comment">
		<div id="div-comment-6165" class="comment-body">
		<div class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
	<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/d22c48810052c48be3559293fa07f85f?s=48&amp;d=retro&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />	<cite itemprop="name"><a itemprop='url' href='http://scribu.net' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>scribu</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	</div>

	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a itemprop="url" href="http://ottopress.com/2010/wordpress-3-1-advanced-taxonomy-queries/comment-page-1/#comment-6165">
		<time itemprop="dateCreated" datetime="2010-12-14T02:29:49+00:00">December 14, 2010 at 2:29 am</time></a>	</div>

	<div itemprop="text"><blockquote><p>The first one is, how can the get_query_var() function be used to get a query var of a certain custom taxonomy or term? Will the parameters available to be fetched via this or via the $_GET ?
</p></blockquote>
<p>Most of the time you should use <code>get_queried_object()</code>.</p>
<p>If not, use <code>$wp_query-&gt;tax_query-&gt;queries</code>.</p>
<p>You should never have to use $_GET.</p>
<blockquote><p>The second is, what will be the url for such a page with multiple taxonomies? will it be rerwitten somehow to a nice permalink, or will it show a long GET parametered url?</p></blockquote>
<p>Multiple taxonomy pages don&#8217;t have pretty URLs yet.</p>
<blockquote><p>what template files in the hierarchy will handle these queries? what will be the specified template names of a specified query and to which general template files it will be call in the hierarchy?</p></blockquote>
<p>The only template file loaded reliably will be taxonomy.php. It&#8217;s up to you to split it up further, as needed. It will also attempt to load {{{taxonomy-{first-tax}.php}}} which I guess will cause some trouble. Don&#8217;t know how to handle that yet.</p>
</div>

