	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-7543" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Comment">
		<div id="div-comment-7543" class="comment-body">
		<div class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
	<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/a3ef151a491ba9259bee86f7fac50499?s=48&amp;d=retro&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />	<cite itemprop="name">Simon</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	</div>

	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a itemprop="url" href="http://ottopress.com/2010/wordpress-3-1-advanced-taxonomy-queries/comment-page-1/#comment-7543">
		<time itemprop="dateCreated" datetime="2011-03-07T14:15:23+00:00">March 7, 2011 at 2:15 pm</time></a>	</div>

	<div itemprop="text"><p>Wow, I&#8217;m very pleased to discover that you can even combine meta_query and tax_query in one query, like so:</p>
<p><code><br />
$query = array(<br />
	'post_type'   =&gt; 'ad',<br />
	'meta_query'  =&gt; array(<br />
			array(<br />
				'key'     =&gt; 'status',<br />
				'value'   =&gt; 'Active',<br />
				'compare' =&gt; 'LIKE'<br />
				)<br />
			),<br />
	'tax_query'   =&gt; array(<br />
			array(<br />
				'taxonomy' =&gt; 'size',<br />
				'terms'    =&gt; array( 'box' ),<br />
				'field'    =&gt; 'slug'<br />
				)<br />
			)<br />
	);<br />
</code></p>
<p>These two additions to WordPress 3.1 have really opened up an exciting range of possibilities.</p>
</div>

